Prosper Loans - Interest Rate Predictors¶

Dataset Overview¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 features. Variables consist of both numeric and categorical types. The attributes included variables that indicate both the borrowers' characteristics (such as whether or not they are homeowners), and the loans features (such as terms, status). 44384 data points were removed due to missing value and outliers before the investigation started.

Investigation Overview¶

My main focus is on finding predictor variables for interest rates (BorrowerRate).

Distribution of Borrower Rates¶

The interest rate is normally distributed between 0 to 0.4, with most loans fall within 0.08 to 0.35, the data has a mode of 0.17. The Borrower APR coloumn is almost identically distributed as the former variable, thus the following discussion will focus on only one, i.e., the BorrowerRate.

Interest Rate vs. Prosper Scores/Terms/Loan Status¶

  • The higher the Prosper score, the lower the interest rates.
  • The longer a loan takes to be repaid, the higher the interest rates.
  • The longer a loan passes its due, the higher the interest rates.

Variables of Personal Financial Situation¶

  • Home owner or not
  • Available bank card credit
  • Income range
  • Monthly income

Interest Rates across ProsperScore, by Homeowner or Not¶

Homeowners pay slightly less interest rate (by around 0.05%) than non-homeowners in general. ProsperScore of between 4 and 7 are the most common. The interest rates varies (standard deviation) within this range, the lowest and highest end of scores has a narrower range of interest rate.
In all scores except for 1.0, homeowners can usually expect to get lower interest rates than non-homeowner counterparts.

Interest Rates across Terms, by Income Ranges¶

Within each income range group, the rate increases as amount of terms increases; overall, for the same amount of terms, people with higher income are able to be granted lower interest rate.

Interest Rates across Different Loan Statuses, by Income Range¶

This graph indicates that for each loan status, it's clear that overall interest rates decrease as income ranges increase. But once a loan is defaulted or charged off, the interest rates can expect to maintain a same level as past due, instead of keeping growing.

Available Bankcard Credits v.s. Interest Rates¶

Despite the amount of loans' terms, the amount of available bankcard credits show a negative correlation to interest rates.

Available bankcard credit v.s. interest rate, by prosper score¶

Borrowers with high ProsperScore mostly have high bankcard credits, and enjoy lowest interest rates (below 0.15). The plots are more clustered in the left lower corner, and have wider spread on the upper side, meaning in the lower scores, bank card credit's role is less important.

Lower bank Card Credits Can be a Barrier to Lowest Rates¶

For borrowers who have the lower interest rate, almost all of them have high bank card credits, whereas stated monthly income is not obviously correlated with the rates.

After understanding that interest rate rises with the longer a loan's due date passed, or its number of terms increases, I extended my investigation of borrowers' financial situations and loans' characteristics. On one hand, I looked into the impact of borrowers' personal situations on the existing correlations between rates and loan types and statuses. On the other hand, as ProsperScore seems to be the strongest indirect indicator, I tried to link its underlying variables directly to interest rates, including DebtToIncomeRatio and TotalInquiries etc.

Less terms and better statuses of loans means lower rates, but it's an indivisual's financial situation that eventually sets the rate. Borrowers with higher bankcard credits and income range, home owners have more chance of receiving lower interest rates.
The negative correlation between income range and interest rate (as observed in the bivariate exploration stage) is confirmed in multivariate exploration. Previously, I found Term has a positive correlation with rates, but it was not clear how borrowers' income ranges' (IncomeRange) negative correlation with rates affect this correlation. In multivariate explotation, it's observed that within each income range group, the rate increases as amount of terms increases, but, for the same amount of terms, people with higher income are able to be granted lower interest rate, despite number of Term.

Similarly, although ProsperScore has a negative correlation with rates, but whether the borrowers are home owners (IsBorrowerHomeowner)still proven to decide whether they can get lower interest rate, i.e., a homeowner who has the same score as a non-homeowner can enjoy lower rates.
Also, interest rates decrease as income ranges increase, despite of different LoanStatus.
Lower bank Card Credits Can be a Barrier to Lowest Rates.
